{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503002"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:53:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1920"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1920"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.46,0.12,0.1,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108365"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1920","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1920"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1920"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90755"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1528"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40439"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108365"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man presents after an episode of sharp right upper quadrant pain that lasted for two hours. He is otherwise in good health. His medical history includes a right hemicolectomy for a Stage IIIB carcinoma of the caecum six years previously. A CT scan at that time did not show any abnormalities apart from the primary tumour. The physical examination is unremarkable. A CT scan is performed and a representative slice shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver cyst","Metastatic deposit","Liver abscess","Gallstones","Haemangioma"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan could have been performed for several reasons, the main one being looking for a cause for the episode of right upper quadrant pain. These symptoms could have been due to biliary colic. Whilst a CT scan is not the best investigation when looking for gallstones, in the real world, abdominal CT scans are - unfortunately - often performed for no good clinical reason.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, here is a solitary lesion in the liver with ring enhancement. It is very unlikely that this lesion would have been responsible for the patient\u0027s episode of acute abdominal pain. However, given the history of a previous colonic resection for carcinoma, \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic disease\u003C/strong\u003E must be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver cysts are common and tend to be of uniform density. This patient would have had an abdominal CT scan as part of his cancer staging six years ago and as this lesion was not seen at that time, it is likely to be something new. A liver cyst has a uniform consistency and no enhancement. A liver abscess is a possible diagnosis - except that the patient is in relative good health. Most patients with a liver abscess will have evidence of sepsis (fever, rigors, general ill-health or weight loss) or pain in the liver region. Haemangiomas are relatively common (incidental) findings and characteristically have peripheral enhancement during the arterial phase - but if this lesion was an haemangioma it would have been evident on the previous CT. Gallstones do not often show up on CT - unless they are well calcified.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Liver lesions with ring enhancement are very likely to be metastatic deposits."],"references":["Schema W, Kolblinger C, Ba-Ssalamah A. Non-invasive diagnosis of focal liver lesions: an individualized approach. Cancer Imaging 2012; 12:365-72."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90755"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1920"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18393"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18393"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aa808c32-e468-4348-9725-dbc62b85aede.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aa808c32-e468-4348-9725-dbc62b85aede.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":549,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90755"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-10T08:17:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-10T08:18:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1920"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108365"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synon